    {{ include_sibling 'instructions.html' }}

{{ endblock }}
This is the most complex template in the app. Let us focus on the new elements.

Buttons instead of radio buttons
The Decision page class has form_fields = ['cooperate'], which means oTree expects the cooperate field to be submitted on this page. But instead of using { formfields } to display the standard radio buttons, this template uses HTML buttons embedded in the payoff matrix:
&lt;button name="cooperate" value="True"
        class="btn btn-primary btn-large"&gt;
    I will cooperate
&lt;/button&gt;
When a participant clicks this button, oTree sets player.cooperate = True and submits the page. The key attributes are:








Attribute
Value
What it does




name
"cooperate"
Must match the field name in form_fields


value
"True"
The value submitted for this field


class
"btn btn-primary btn-large"
Bootstrap classes for a styled blue button



This approach integrates the form submission directly into the payoff matrix, so participants can make their choice by clicking a button in the relevant row of the table. There is no separate Next button — clicking either button submits the form and advances the page.






Note{ formfields } vs. custom buttons



You have two options for collecting form data:

{ formfields } — Automatically renders all fields in form_fields as standard inputs (radio buttons, text fields, etc.). Simple and reliable.
Custom HTML buttons — You write the buttons yourself using &lt;button name="..." value="..."&gt;. This gives you full control over layout and appearance.

The custom approach is more work but lets you place inputs exactly where you want them — for example, inside a payoff matrix.




The { chat } widget
{{ chat }}
This single tag adds oTree’s built-in chat widget to the page. Participants in the same group can send messages to each other in real time. This is included in the sample app to demonstrate the feature, but you would typically only use it if your experimental design requires communication between participants.






NoteYou probably will not use { chat } in your assignment



The Stag Hunt assignment does not require a chat feature. When you build your own app, you can simply leave this out. It is included here because the Prisoner’s Dilemma sample is designed to showcase oTree’s capabilities.

Results.html: conditional display
{{ block title }}Results{{ endblock }}
{{ block content }}

    &lt;p&gt;
        {{ if same_choice }}
            Both of you chose to {{ my_decision }}.
        {{ else }}
            You chose to {{ my_decision }} and the other participant
            chose to {{ opponent_decision }}.
        {{ endif }}
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
        As a result, you earned {{ player.payoff }}.
    &lt;/p&gt;

    {{ next_button }}

    {{ include_sibling 'instructions.html' }}

{{ endblock }}
This template introduces two important template features.

{ if } / { else } / { endif }: conditional display
{{ if same_choice }}
    Both of you chose to {{ my_decision }}.
{{ else }}
    You chose to {{ my_decision }} and the other participant
    chose to {{ opponent_decision }}.
{{ endif }}
This is the template equivalent of a Python if/else statement. It controls which text is shown based on a condition:

If same_choice is True (both players made the same decision), the first paragraph appears.
If same_choice is False, the second paragraph appears instead.

The variable same_choice was created in vars_for_template in the Results page class. Any Boolean variable can be used as a condition in { if }.






NoteTemplate { if } syntax



The full syntax supports several patterns:
{{/* Simple condition */}}
{{ if variable }}
    Shown when variable is True (or non-empty)
{{ endif }}

{{/* If/else */}}
{{ if variable }}
    Shown when True
{{ else }}
    Shown when False
{{ endif }}

{{/* Comparisons */}}
{{ if player.round_number == 1 }}
    This is the first round.
{{ endif }}

{{ if player.payoff &gt; 0 }}
    You earned something!
{{ endif }}
Always close your { if } blocks with { endif }. Forgetting { endif } will cause a template error.




Displaying variables from vars_for_template
{{ my_decision }}
{{ opponent_decision }}
{{ player.payoff }}
Variables created in vars_for_template (like my_decision and opponent_decision) are accessed by name. Built-in variables (like player.payoff) are accessed using dot notation. Both use the { } syntax.

Step 2: show the introduction only in round 1
With NUM_ROUNDS = 5, the Introduction page currently appears in every round — participants would re-read the instructions five times. You need to restrict it to round 1 only.
Add an is_displayed method to the Introduction page class:
class Introduction(Page):
    timeout_seconds = 100

    @staticmethod
    def is_displayed(player):
        return player.round_number == 1
is_displayed returns True or False. If it returns True, the page appears. If False, the page is skipped for that round. Here, player.round_number == 1 is True only in the first round, so the instructions appear once and are skipped in rounds 2 through 5.






Noteplayer.round_number



Every player object has a built-in attribute called round_number that tells you the current round. It starts at 1 (not 0) and goes up to NUM_ROUNDS.


You can use is_displayed to show any page conditionally. For example, if you wanted a page to appear only in round 4 to announce a rule change, you would write:
@staticmethod
def is_displayed(player):
    return player.round_number == 4

Step 6: display the history table in the template
Open Decision.html and add the history table. Place it above or below the payoff matrix — wherever you think participants will find it most useful. Here is the HTML:
{{ if game_history }}
&lt;h4&gt;Game History&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;table class="table table-bordered text-center" style="width: auto; margin: auto"&gt;
    &lt;thead&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Round&lt;/th&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Your Choice&lt;/th&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Your Payoff&lt;/th&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Partner's Choice&lt;/th&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Partner's Payoff&lt;/th&gt;
            &lt;th&gt;Cumulative Payoff&lt;/th&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/thead&gt;
    &lt;tbody&gt;
        {{ for row in game_history }}
        &lt;tr&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;{{ row.round }}&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;{{ row.my_choice }}&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;{{ row.my_payoff }}&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;{{ row.partner_choice }}&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;{{ row.partner_payoff }}&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;{{ row.cumulative }}&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
        {{ endfor }}
    &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
{{ endif }}
Let us go through the new template features.

{ if game_history }: checking if the list is non-empty
{{ if game_history }}
    ...
{{ endif }}
In round 1, game_history is an empty list. In oTree templates (and Python), an empty list is “falsy” — it evaluates to False in a condition. So the entire table is hidden in round 1 (when there is no history to show) and appears from round 2 onward.


{ for row in game_history }: looping through rows
{{ for row in game_history }}
&lt;tr&gt;
    &lt;td&gt;{{ row.round }}&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;td&gt;{{ row.my_choice }}&lt;/td&gt;
    ...
&lt;/tr&gt;
{{ endfor }}
This is the template equivalent of a Python for loop. It repeats the &lt;tr&gt;...&lt;/tr&gt; block once for each entry in game_history. Each time through the loop, row takes on the next dictionary from the list, and you access its values with dot notation: { row.round }, { row.my_choice }, etc.
Always close { for } loops with { endfor }.


&lt;thead&gt; and &lt;tbody&gt;
These are standard HTML tags that separate the header row(s) from the data rows. &lt;thead&gt; wraps the column headers. &lt;tbody&gt; wraps the data. They have no visual effect by default but help with accessibility and some CSS styling.

Step 10: add images and styled text
The assignment requires visual elements — happy/sad face images on the results page and role-specific text colours. Let us practice both.

Adding images with { static }
To display an image in a template, you need two things: the image file in the right folder, and an &lt;img&gt; tag in the template.
Step 1: Place your image files (e.g., happy.png and sad.png) in the _static/ folder at the top level of your project — the same level as settings.py.
Step 2: Reference them in your template using { static }:
{{ if same_choice }}
    &lt;img src="{{ static 'happy.png' }}" alt="Happy face" width="80"&gt;
{{ else }}
    &lt;img src="{{ static 'sad.png' }}" alt="Sad face" width="80"&gt;
{{ endif }}
The { static 'filename' } tag generates the correct URL for files in the _static/ folder. The alt attribute provides text for screen readers (accessibility), and width controls the display size in pixels.






TipWhere to find free images



You can find simple emoji-style images for free on sites like OpenMoji or Twemoji. Download the image files and place them in your _static/ folder. Make sure the filenames match exactly what you write in the template.




Styling text with CSS
You can style any text in a template using inline CSS or CSS classes. For example, to display a role name in bold red:
&lt;span style="color: red; font-weight: bold;"&gt;Hunter 1&lt;/span&gt;
Or in italic green:
&lt;span style="color: green; font-style: italic;"&gt;Hunter 2&lt;/span&gt;
For something you will reuse many times, define CSS classes at the top of your template:
&lt;style&gt;
    .role1 { color: red; font-weight: bold; }
    .role2 { color: green; font-style: italic; }
&lt;/style&gt;
Then apply them using the class attribute:
{{ if player.role == C.PLAYER1_ROLE }}
    &lt;span class="role1"&gt;{{ player.role }}&lt;/span&gt;
{{ else }}
    &lt;span class="role2"&gt;{{ player.role }}&lt;/span&gt;
{{ endif }}






NoteInline styles vs. CSS classes



Inline styles (style="color: red;") are fine for one-off use. But if you need the same style in many places — like colouring every mention of a role — CSS classes are much more efficient. Define the class once, then use class="role1" wherever you need it.

Page classes

Basic page
class MyPage(Page):
    form_model = 'player'                 # Which model the form saves to
    form_fields = ['field1', 'field2']     # Which fields appear on the page


Page methods








Method
When it runs
Common use




is_displayed(player)
Before the page is shown
Skip pages conditionally


vars_for_template(player)
Before rendering the template
Pass calculated data to HTML


before_next_page(player, timeout_happened)
After form submission
Set defaults, do calculations


app_after_this_page(player, upcoming_apps)
After the page
Skip to a different app entirely



class Decision(Page):
    form_model = 'player'
    form_fields = ['stag']
    timeout_seconds = 60

    @staticmethod
    def is_displayed(player):
        return player.round_number == 1

    @staticmethod
    def vars_for_template(player):
        return dict(my_variable=some_value)

    @staticmethod
    def before_next_page(player, timeout_happened):
        if timeout_happened:
            player.stag = True

    @staticmethod
    def app_after_this_page(player, upcoming_apps):
        if some_condition:
            return upcoming_apps[0]    # Skip to the next app


Wait pages
class MyWaitPage(WaitPage):
    after_all_players_arrive = my_function    # Runs once when all players arrive
Or with a method defined inline:
class MyWaitPage(WaitPage):
    @staticmethod
    def after_all_players_arrive(group):
        # Calculate payoffs, check stopping rule, etc.
        for p in group.get_players():
            set_payoff(p)


Custom wait page template
class MyWaitPage(WaitPage):
    template_name = __name__ + '/MyWaitPage.html'
    title_text = "Waiting for other participants..."

    @staticmethod
    def vars_for_template(player):
        return dict(my_data=some_value)
Wait pages can also have vars_for_template to pass data to the custom template.

Skipping rounds and apps

Skipping to the next app with app_after_this_page
@staticmethod
def app_after_this_page(player, upcoming_apps):
    if player.participant.finished_rounds:
        return upcoming_apps[0]    # Jump to the next app in app_sequence
upcoming_apps is a list of app names remaining in app_sequence. Returning upcoming_apps[0] sends the player to the very next app, skipping all remaining rounds.
Return None (or do not return anything) to continue normally.

